## The matter power spectrum

The curvature perturbation $P_\zeta$ itself cannot be directly measured. But because GR says that spacetime curvature and energy–matter density go hand-in-hand, we could measure at the latter instead. In this case, the relevant quantity is the Newtonian potential $\Phi$, and as a consequence of GR, $P_\Phi \propto P_\zeta$.

From perturbation theory, the potential at late times is given by Poisson’s equation
\begin{align}
\nabla^2 \Phi = -4\pi G \bar{\rho}_\text{m} a^2 \delta \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad k^2 \Phi_k = 4\pi G \bar{\rho}_\text{m} a^2 \delta_k.
\end{align} Since $\bar{\rho}_\text{m} = \Omega_\text{m} \rho_\text{cr}/a^3$ (by definition) and $4\pi G \rho_\text{cr} = (3/2) H_0^2$ (from the Friedmann equations),
\begin{align}
\delta(\mathbf{k},a) = \frac{k^2 \Phi(\mathbf{k},a) \,a}{(3/2)\Omega_\text{m} H_0^2}.
\end{align}

Schematically, the potential at a given scale factor $a(t)$ can be obtained from the primordial potential via
\begin{align}
\Phi(\mathbf{k},a) &= \Phi_\text{p}(\mathbf{k}) \times \text{Transfer function}(k) \times \text{Growth function}(a) \\
&= \frac{9}{10} \Phi_\text{p}(\mathbf{k}) \,T(k) \frac{D_1(a)}{a} \; \text{by convention}.
\end{align}

The density perturbation is then
\begin{align}
\delta(\mathbf{k},a) = \frac{3}{5} \frac{k^2}{\Omega_\text{m} H_0^2} \Phi_\text{p}(\mathbf{k}) \,T(k) \,D_1(a),
\end{align} and its power spectrum can be seen (by squaring both sides) to take the form
\begin{align}
P_\delta(k) \propto k^4 P_\Phi(k) \,T^2(k).
\end{align}

From the Boltzmann fluid equations, it can be shown that
\begin{align}
T(k) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{radiation-dominated era},\\
(k_\text{eq}/k)^2 & \text{matter-dominated era},
\end{cases}
\end{align} where $k_\text{eq}$ is the scale that _re-entered_ the horizon at matter–radiation equality.

Finally, because $P_\Phi \propto P_\zeta \propto k^{n_s - 1}$, we can say that the power spectrum of matter density perturbations is
\begin{align}
P(k) \propto
\begin{cases}
k^{n_s} & \text{radiation-dominated era},\\
k^{n_s-4} & \text{matter-dominated era}.
\end{cases}
\end{align} Inserting $n_s \approx 1$ will produce a plot of the matter power spectrum that is well matched by observations.
